<p>Dear Reader,<br />
I am an experienced software engineer; with a focus on interaction design, and information visualisation.  To support the user journeys “assist the user to find the information they want” and “solve the users immediate problem”, I have been spending most (e.g. 60%) of my time building things in languages that run inside a webrowser.  As a child I was very focussed on drawing, and graphical composition (I have five qualifications in art related stuff).  I use these skills as an adult, in terms page design, and data chunking.   Nearly all my commercial experience is in startups, which implies I am used to mixed responsibilities, and maximising return value.   This year I went to a remote conference, on data visualisation; last year I went to a JS remote conference.    <br />
I expect this to be common, but I have quite a few years trying to provide quality on systems that are quite hard to test.  My reaction to this is that I have written quite a few OSS test tools and scripts.   Since I was 16, I have built server-side systems in Java, Perl, Python, C++, Golang, PHP, NodeJS<a class="" href="https://www.google.co.uk/search?q=NodeJS">?</a>.  I am only mentioning the recent ones on my CV.  I have used many frameworks.</p>

<p>I am currently applying to companies in the Netherlands, and Amsterdam in particular.  Assisted by not commuting, and the lock-downs; I have been studying Dutch for a year and a half; as I think it is important to be able to communicate with my intended peers.   If you interview you me, I will talk in Dutch in the interview.  I wrote <a class="" href="http://owenberesford.me.uk/resource/whats-changed-2020#">whats-changed-2020</a> in Dutch; but I think this shows that I am not fluent more strongly than I am fluent<br />
I was born in the UK, but disagree with the economic engineering of Brexit.  I wish to work in an European city, and withdraw all assets from the UK.   I am planning to permanently move to Amsterdam, with relevant paperwork.   I would have like to been writing to you in the start in 2020, but Covid19 stalled my plans.   As a process, I think it is more practical to work remote for a short period ~ due to covid19; then complete the move when the European/UK levels of infection are smaller.   I am happy with any sensible process suggested.  I have several years experience working remotely; and for software engineering its quite practical.</p>


</div>
